# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afghanistan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] The **2017 ECO summit** was the 13th summit of the Economic Cooperation Organization, held on 1 March 2017 in Islamabad, Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] The Summit was preceded by the 22nd Meeting of the ECO Council of Foreign Ministers (COM) on 28 February 2017 in Islamabad.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] Senior Officials from Member States met on 27 February 2017 in Islamabad and stayed for the duration of the summit.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] The summit highlighted the state of affairs of ECO in the light of the new and emerging global and regional circumstances and agreed on expanding regional economic cooperation among its member states.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] The new *ECO Vision 2025* was expanded upon and several key guidelines have been taken into account.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] Pakistan plans to integrate the ECO Summit members with the China–Pakistan Economic Corridor.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] According to *The News International*, Islamabad intended to use the five billion rupees' worth of resources initially allocated for 19th SAARC summit, will be used for ECO Summit.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] Prime Minister Sharif also hosted an informal dinner in the honour of Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdoğan and his wife Emine Erdoğan at the Prime Ministers House.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] On February 27, 2017, Pakistan's Ministry of Interior drafted a comprehensive security plan for the summit.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] Under the plan, local holiday was declared in the Islamabad-Rawalpindi metropolitan area on March 1 while on February 28, after 1 pm, educational institutions and offices were to be closed.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] Kashmir Highway will also be partially closed during the summit.
[src:afghanistan/13th-eco-summit] The army was given responsibility for the security of the Red Zone within the city.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Summits of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) were held from 1985 to 2014.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] As of 2026, a summit has not been held since the 18th summit in Nepal.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The SAARC Charter requires summits approximately every eighteen months.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The first summit was held in Dhaka, Bangladesh on 7–8 December 1985 and was attended by the Government representative and president of Bangladesh, Maldives, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, the kings of Bhutan and Nepal, and the Prime Minister of India.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] They signed the SAARC Charter on 8 December 1985, establishing the regional association, study groups on the problems of terrorism and drug trafficking.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] They also planned a meeting about GATT and a conference on increasing the participation of women at the regional level.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The summit also agreed to establish a SAARC secretariat and adopted an official SAARC emblem.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The second summit was held on November 17–18 1986 in Bangalore, India.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The leaders welcomed the signing of the Memorandum of Understanding on the establishment of the SAARC Secretariat by the Council of Ministers and their decision to locate the Secretariat in Kathmandu and appoint Ambassador Abul Ahsan of Bangladesh as the first Secretary-General of SAARC.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The third summit was held in Kathmandu, Nepal from 2–4 November 1987, and was attended by the Presidents of Bangladesh, the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the Prime Ministers of India and Pakistan, and the kings of Bhutan and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The foreign ministers of the member states signed the SAARC Regional Convention on Suppression of Terrorism and an agreement to establish a South Asian Food Reserve.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The fourth summit was held in Islamabad, Pakistan on 29–31 December 1988 and was attended by the presidents of Bangladesh, the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of India and Pakistan, and the kings of Bhutan and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] They discussed the coup attempt on 3 November 1988, announced themes for future SAARC summits, and launched a regional plan with socio-economic targets for the end of the century.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] It was also agreed to hold regular "South Asian Festivals" with the first being hosted by India.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The fifth summit was held in Malé, Maldives on 21–23 November 1990 and was attended by the presidents of Bangladesh, the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of India, Nepal and Pakistan, and the king of Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The leaders launched the Special SAARC Travel Document (for dignitaries, academics, and their families) and signed agreements on narcotics and tourism.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] They also authorized the SAARC Secretariat to share information and research with the European Community and ASEAN, and expanded on themes for future SAARC summits from 1991-2000, the "SAARC Decade of the Girl Child".
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The sixth summit was held in Colombo, Sri Lanka on 21 December 1991 and was attended by the prime ministers of Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Pakistan, the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka, and the king of Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The seventh summit was held in Dhaka, on 10–11 April 1993 and attended by the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Pakistan, and the king of Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The eighth summit was held in New Delhi, on 2–4 May 1995, and was attended by the presidents of the Maldives, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of Bangladesh, India and Nepal, and the king of Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The ninth summit was held in Malé, on 12–14 May 1997, and was attended by the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of Bangladesh, India, Nepal and Pakistan, and the king of Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The tenth summit was held in Colombo, on 29–31 July 1998, and was attended by the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka and the prime ministers of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal and Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] SAARC countries stressed the need to eradicate poverty and promote joint collaboration.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The eleventh summit was held in Kathmandu, on 4–6 January 2002, and was attended by the presidents of the Maldives, Pakistan and Sri Lanka and the prime ministers of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The twelfth summit was held in Islamabad, on 4–6 January 2004, and was attended by the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka and the prime ministers of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal and Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The areas of focus were science and technological cooperation across the region, and the South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA).
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The thirteenth summit was held in Dhaka, on 12–13 November 2005, and was attended by the prime ministers of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India and Pakistan, the presidents of the Maldives and Sri Lanka, and the king of Nepal and Bhutan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The fourteenth summit of SAARC was held in New Delhi, India on 3-4 April 2007, and was attended by the presidents of Afghanistan, the Maldives and Sri Lanka, the prime ministers of Bhutan, India, Nepal and Pakistan, and the chief adviser of the government of Bangladesh.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The summit stressed the need to improve intra-regional connectivity.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The fifteenth summit of SAARC was held in Colombo, Sri Lanka on 1–3 August 2008.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The issues discussed included: regional cooperation, the global food crisis, socio-economic development, the environment, culture, combating terrorism, and the admission of Australia and Myanmar as observers.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The sixteenth summit was held in Thimphu, Bhutan on 28–29 April 2010.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The central issue was climate change, with the summit titled "Towards a Green and Happy South Asia".
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The leaders signed a SAARC Convention on Cooperation on Environment and pledged to plant 10 million trees over the next 5 years.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] India offered support to member countries for developing sustainable energy technologies, capacity building, and climate adaption.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The seventeenth summit was held from 10-11 of November 2011 in Addu City, Maldives.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The meeting was held at the Equatorial Convention Centre, Addu City.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The Secretary General of SAARC commented on how the summit theme of "Building Bridges" could galvanise action on: economic and income inequality; gender inequality; and the gap between intent and implementation.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] In addition, the Addu Declaration of the Seventeenth SAARC summit was adopted.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The 18th SAARC summit was held at the Nepalese capital Kathmandu from November 26 to November 27, 2014 and was attended by the prime ministers of Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal and Pakistan, and the presidents of the Afghanistan, Maldives and Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The motto was ‘Deeper Integration for Peace and Prosperity’.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The SAARC Satellite Scheme was authorised at this summit.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] The scheme will be developed in all member nations except Bangladesh and Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Pakistan was scheduled to host the 19th summit of South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) in Islamabad on 15 to 16 November 2016.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Following the 2016 Uri terror attack, India cancelled its participation in the 19th SAARC summit, alleging Pakistan's involvement in the terror attack.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in his address to the 19th SAARC summit being held in the Pakistan’s capital, said that the objective of this summit was to address the security issues between India and Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Hours after Indian PM Narendra Modi decided to boycott the SAARC summit in Islamabad in the wake of Uri terror attack.
[src:afghanistan/17th-saarc-summit] Bangladesh, Afghanistan, Bhutan, Maldives and Sri Lanka also pulled out of the summit.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] The eighteenth summit of 'South Asian Association of Regional Cooperation' (SAARC) was held in Kathmandu, the capital of Federal Democratic Republic of Nepal during 26–27 November 2014.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] The theme of the summit was *Deeper Integration for Peace and Prosperity*, focused on enhancing connectivity between the member states for easier transit-transport across the region.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] Sushil Koirala, the then Nepalese prime minister, was the main host of the event which took place in Rastriya Sabha Griha The summit took place after an interval of three years as the previous summit was held in 2011 in Maldives.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] There it was agreed to revitalize the SAARC initiative and a summit was agreed upon in Nepal at the earliest.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] The following heads of state/heads of government of the eight member countries participated in the summit in Kathmandu.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] Foreign Ministers of the eight member states signed an agreement on energy cooperation namely 'SAARC Framework Agreement for Energy Cooperation (Electricity)' in the presence of their heads of state and government during the concluding ceremony of the 18th SAARC Summit on 27 November.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] Although Pakistan stalled, citing insufficient internal preparations, signing of two other agreements on Vehicular Traffic and Railways respectively.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] It was also decided that Pakistan will host the next summit in 2016.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] The India-Pakistan stand-off on the first day threatened to jeopardize the entire summit process as Pakistan seemed to be in the mood to block every Indian led proposal.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] Pakistan, China's all weather friend, also vouched for a more participatory role for the observer nations in the summit process, indirectly advocating for a more Chinese involvement.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] Although no such proposal was accepted because of India's reservation.
[src:afghanistan/18th-saarc-summit] With the ongoing cold relationships between India and Pakistan, the formal handshake between the prime ministers from both the countries caught a lot of attention and was applauded by everyone in the Summit Hall.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The **1923 Constitution of Afghanistan** was the first written constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Drafted during the reign of King Amanullah Khan and ratified by a loya jirga convened in Jalalabad in 1922, it formally came into force on 9 April 1923.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The first constitutional assembly was called "The Council of State".
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution established Afghanistan as a sovereign Islamic monarchy, defined the powers and responsibilities of the state, and sought to modernize the country's administrative, judicial, and educational institutions.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] It also contained provisions on civil rights, taxation, and the abolition of slavery and forced labor.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The document constituted a central element of Amanullah's programme of state modernization following Afghan independence from British suzerainty after the Third Anglo-Afghan War (1919) and the subsequent Treaty of Rawalpindi.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution was amended once, on 28 January 1925, following pressure from conservative tribal and religious groups during the Khost rebellion of 1924–1925.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] It was superseded by the 1931 Constitution after the abdication of Amanullah Khan.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Following the death of Habibullah Khan in February 1919, his son Amanullah Khan ascended to the Afghan throne and immediately declared full Afghan independence from British suzerainty.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The Third Anglo-Afghan War, which lasted from May to August 1919, ended with the Treaty of Rawalpindi, by which the United Kingdom relinquished its control over Afghanistan's foreign affairs.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Afghanistan thus became a fully sovereign state for the first time in the modern sense, free to conduct its own diplomatic relations.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The restoration of full sovereignty created both an opportunity and a necessity for internal reform.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Amanullah sought to transform Afghanistan from a loosely organized tribal polity into a modern, centralized nation-state capable of engaging with the international community on equal terms.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Following independence, Amanullah initiated an ambitious programme of political, legal, social, and educational reform.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Influenced by the modernizing states of the Ottoman Empire and Iran, as well as European constitutional models and Islamic modernist thought, his government sought to codify laws that had previously existed in a diffuse or informal state.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Central to this project was the creation of a written constitution, a document that would formally define the relationship between the state and its subjects, and legitimize the new order both domestically and internationally.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution was drafted by legal commissions composed of both Afghan officials and foreign advisors.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The drafting process drew on the legal traditions of Ottoman constitutional law, Hanafi Islamic jurisprudence, and elements of European constitutional practice.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The original text was composed in Pashto and subsequently translated into Dari (Persian); the surviving text most widely consulted by scholars is the Persian translation.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The original text of the constitution was composed in Pashto.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The surviving document is a Persian translation, which explicitly identifies itself as such.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The document was printed on 10 April 1923 in 2,500 copies, the day after it formally came into force.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution was approved by a Loya jirga, a grand assembly of tribal leaders, religious scholars (*ulema*), nobles, and government officials — convened in Jalalabad in the eastern province (*mashriqi*) of Afghanistan in 1922.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] A total of 872 members of the assembly signed and sealed the document.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Following royal assent by King Amanullah, it formally came into force on 9 April 1923 (20 Hamal 1302 in the Afghan solar calendar).
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The 1923 Constitution consisted of 73 articles and established Afghanistan as an independent and sovereign monarchy under Islam.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution vested responsibility for government administration in the Council of Ministers and independent departments.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The king served as chairman of the council; in his absence, the prime minister presided.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Ministers were selected and appointed by the king and were individually responsible to him for both the general policy of government and their personal conduct in office.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The Council of Ministers was charged with formulating foreign and domestic policy.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Decisions of the council, as well as treaties and agreements, required royal ratification to take effect.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] A special annual high assembly (*darbar-e-ali*) was to be convened each year before the independence celebrations, at which ministers and heads of departments would report on their achievements to an audience of senior officials, tribal elders, nobles, and royal appointees.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Ministers were subject to trial for official misconduct before a high court (*diwan-e-ali*) constituted on a temporary basis for that purpose; for personal misconduct outside their official duties they were subject to the ordinary courts as private citizens.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution established a State Council in the capital and local advisory councils in the provinces and district centers.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Membership in these councils was composed of both appointed and elected members in equal numbers; appointed members of the State Council were directly selected by the king, while elected members were chosen by the people in accordance with separate electoral provisions.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The State Council was given the function of reviewing legislation proposed by the government before it was transmitted to the Council of Ministers and thereafter to the king for ratification.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] It was also charged with reviewing the annual budget prepared by the Ministry of Finance and scrutinizing all contracts, treaties, and agreements concluded by the government with foreign parties.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] All trials were declared to be public, with exceptions for specified matters prescribed by a separate law on courts.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Citizens and litigants were entitled to use all legitimate means to protect their rights before a court.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Courts were required to avoid delay in hearing cases and were declared free from all forms of interference.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] No special court to hear a particular case could be established outside the regular judicial framework.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] All courts were to decide disputes in accordance with the principles of the sharia and applicable civil and criminal laws (Art.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] A High Court for the trial of ministers was to be established on a temporary basis as needed and dissolved upon the completion of its work.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] All state taxes were to be collected under applicable taxation law.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] An annual budget detailing government revenues and expenditures was to be prepared, and an end-of-year financial report reconciling actual revenues and expenditures against the budget was required.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution provided for the establishment of an auditing office with the function of reporting on whether revenues and expenditures had corresponded to the budget.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Provincial administration was based on three principles: decentralization of authority; clear delineation of duties; and clear determination of responsibilities.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Branch offices of the ministries were to be established in the provinces.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Citizens were to seek initial redress from these provincial branches, with recourse to superior officials and provincial governors available when local officials were unable or unwilling to act in accordance with law.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The government was empowered to proclaim military administration in any part of the country experiencing disobedience or rebellion threatening public security.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Resistance to Amanullah's reform programme emerged from conservative tribal and religious factions, particularly in the eastern and southern regions.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The Khost rebellion of 1924–1925, led by the Mangal tribe and given a religious dimension by local religious leaders (*mullahs*) who sided with the rebels, challenged the constitutional order and accused the monarchy of departing from Islamic tradition.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Amanullah initially attempted negotiation, offering to dispatch a delegation of religious scholars from Kabul to discuss the objections raised by the tribal clergy.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] When those talks failed to reach agreement, he convened a second loya jirga in Paghman in late 1924.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The assembly recommended a series of amendments, and the amended constitution was reissued with royal assent on 28 January 1925.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The 1923 constitution is widely regarded as the foundation of modern constitutionalism in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] It represented the first formal attempt to define the relationship between the monarchy, the state, and Afghan citizens through a written legal document.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Although many of Amanullah's reforms faced criticism and were partially reversed after his overthrow in 1929, the constitution established important precedents for later Afghan constitutions, including those of 1931 and 1964.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Modern historians have described the constitution as a synthesis of Islamic legal modernism, influence of Ottoman constitution, and Afghan state-building traditions.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] The 1923 constitution laid the structural foundation for subsequent Afghan constitutional development, influencing the drafting of the 1931 Constitution drafted under Mohammed Nadir Shah, as well as later constitutions in 1964 and 1977.
[src:afghanistan/1923-constitution-of-afghanistan] Many of its structural features, a Council of Ministers, provincial councils, a bicameral advisory state body, and codified judicial procedures, were retained in modified form in later Afghan constitutional documents.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The **1964 Constitution of Afghanistan** was the supreme law of the Kingdom of Afghanistan from 1964 to 1973.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] It was annulled following a coup d'état, though parts of the constitution were restored by future governments from 2002 to 2004 and from 2021 to 2022.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] It was initially drafted by a committee of seven members appointed for the task by the then-king of Afghanistan, Mohammad Zahir Shah.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The committee consisted primarily of figures closely associated with the government.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Its members were then-Minister of Justice, Sayyid Shamsuddin Majrooh; Said Qassim Rishtya; Mir Najmuddin Ansari; Mohammad Mossa Shafiq; Abdul Samad Hamed; Hamidullah; and Mir Mohammad Siddiq Farhang.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] All except Hamidullah were associated with government ministries, while Hamidullah was a professor at Kabul University.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The primary goals of the Constitution were to prepare the government and the people for gradual democratization and socioeconomic modernization.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] It also acknowledged freedom of assembly, freedom of association, and freedom of speech.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] A Loya jirga (grand council of notables) had debated, modified and approved its innovations, which included a bill of rights for all Afghans, explicitly including women.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] After public review, the constitution was put into effect in October 1964.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Although Afghanistan became a sovereign nation in 1747 under the rule of Ahmad Shah Durrani, the earliest Afghan constitution was written during the reign of Emir Abdur Rahman Khan in the 1890s followed by a 1923 version.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The 1964 Constitution transformed Afghanistan into a modern democracy.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] A new parliament was created, dominated by its lower house (the Wolesi Jirgah), which was to be elected through universal suffrage.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] It had the power to reject royal appointments to the cabinet and to dismiss it by a vote of no confidence.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Laws passed by parliament were to have constitutional precedence over traditional Islamic law (the Sharia).
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Parliament was to meet regularly, not at royal pleasure as before.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] It could refuse budget increases, but could not reduce appropriations below the level of the previous year.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Its members had control over the organization of parliament and enjoyed legal immunity for what they said in debate.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Members had the right to form political parties, but their formation required legislation acceptable to the cabinet and, hence, the king.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Bold as its innovations were compared with the functional autocracy it replaced, the constitution was filled with provisions intended to assure that the royal government would not lose control.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] A wide constitutional gulf separated the cabinet from the parliament.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The cabinet was to exercise the monarch's powers, including the initiation of all government policy and the invocation of emergency decrees.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Cooperation between officials and legislators, integral to classical parliamentary systems, was discouraged.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Legislators were prohibited from holding ministerial or other executive positions.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The cabinet was assured control over the composition of the Meshrano Jirgah, the parliament's upper house.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution also established Afghanistan as a unitary state and administrative subdivisions like provinces, districts, subdistricts, and rural and urban municipalities were under the orders of the central government.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Powers were also restricted and local leaders were appointed by the president.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution called forelected local councils, however the law responsible for the implementation of said councils wasn't passed.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Judicial restructuring and elective provincial councils were endorsed, but the constitution did not prescribe their structure or working arrangements.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The failure to spell out a complete structure for the government lent a provisional character to the constitution.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] At least seventy articles required parliamentary legislation in order for them to take effect.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution's democratic features were especially provisional.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Ample authority was retained for the executive branch to slow, halt or reverse legislation.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Nor was caution only displayed toward would-be overweening legislators.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The most notorious provision in the constitution was its prohibition of official or political activity by any member of the royal family other than the monarch.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The implications of this clause would soon haunt the constitutionalists.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] No means was provided for an increasingly restless Muhammad Daud, a cousin of the King and former Prime Minister of Afghanistan from 1953 to 1963, to return to power without nullifying the constitution.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Shortly after its enactment, the vulnerability of the constitution to political realities became dramatically clear.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The adversarial relationship it created between the cabinet and the parliament brought about tragedy and a serious loss of political momentum.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] In October 1965, following the election of the new legislature, an impasse over its approval of the new cabinet brought about rioting and intervention by the army leading to the death of at least three student demonstrators.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The proposed cabinet was withdrawn, following which a reshuffled one under the leadership of Mohammad Hashim Maiwandwal, a senior diplomat, was approved with little opposition.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Officials and legislators were faced with running the new system with hopes considerably dampened.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The liberal or constitutional experiment, which lasted for the next eight years, has been generally seen as a political failure.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The cabinet and legislature were constantly deadlocked, unable to enact laws vital to the constitution or seriously weakening it through long delays.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Legislators proved to be effective critics of the bureaucracy, which responded by holding back legislation to avoid scrutiny or lengthy disputes.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] There was a wide social and cultural gap between the legislators and senior ministry officials.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Few of the former had had the exposure to the modern education and foreign experience enjoyed by senior ministry officials.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] More than 90 percent of the Wolesi Jirgah members represented rural constituencies.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Legislators had the right to lobby ministers and senior bureaucrats directly.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] Doing so was more rewarding than dealing with middle rank provincial officials who had less authority and information.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] The constitution discouraged executive-legislative cooperation on policy, but it did not prevent the give and take of patronage.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] After the 2021 Taliban takeover of Afghanistan, the new authorities declared the restoration of parts of the 1964 constitution that are "not in conflict with Islamic Sharia (law)" to govern the country in the interim.
[src:afghanistan/1964-constitution-of-afghanistan] However, this decision was overturned by Supreme Leader Hibatullah Akhundzada; it was announced to the public in August 2022 that he had earlier made the decision not to use the 1964 constitution on the basis that it is incompatible with Sharia.
[src:afghanistan/af] The .af domain was delegated to Abdul Razeeq in 1997, a year after Taliban fighters had captured Kabul and founded the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/af] NetNames of London initially maintained the domain following an agreement with the IANA.
[src:afghanistan/af] Razeeq later disappeared, halting some services.
[src:afghanistan/af] The domain was reopened on 10 March 2003, as a joint program between UNDP and the Afghan Ministry of Communications.
[src:afghanistan/af] As of 26 August 2020, .af was used by 5,960 domains.
[src:afghanistan/af] With the fall of Kabul in 2021, the .af domain again came under the control of the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan/af] ICANN said it "defers decision making to within the country".
[src:afghanistan/af] Registration is made directly at the second level, or on the third level beneath various categorised subdomains at the second level.
[src:afghanistan/af] Third-level domains have restrictions based on which second-level domain they are registered under.
[src:afghanistan/af] Registration on the second level is unrestricted, but more expensive.
[src:afghanistan/af] All fees are higher for international registrants.
[src:afghanistan/af] In 2024, a number of .af domains including "broke.af" and "queer.af" went offline.
[src:afghanistan/af] The Afghan Ministry of Communications and IT said that they were registered through Gandi, a France-based domain name registrar, and cited Gandi's failure to make payments as the reason for suspension.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to Deutsche Welle in September 2021, 250 remain in the country after 67 were evacuated to India.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] There was a small Jewish community in Afghanistan, living mainly in Herat and Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Over the years, this small community was forced to leave due to decades of warfare and religious persecution.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] By the end of the twentieth century, nearly the entire community had emigrated to Israel and the United States, with one known exception, Herat-born Zablon Simintov.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] He remained for years, being the caretaker of the only remaining Afghan synagogue.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] He left the country for the US after the second Taliban takeover.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] A woman who left shortly after him has since been identified as the likely last Jew in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Christians, who number 500–8,000, practice their faith secretly due to intense societal opposition, and there are no public churches.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Education in Afghanistan is overseen by the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Higher Education.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] There are over 16,000 schools in the country and roughly 9 million students.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Of this, about 60% are males and 40% females.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] However, the new regime has thus far forbidden female teachers and female students from returning to secondary schools.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Over 174,000 students are enrolled in different universities around the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Former Education Minister Ghulam Farooq Wardak had stated that construction of 8,000 schools is required for the remaining children who are deprived of formal learning.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of 2018 the literacy rate of the population age 15 and older is 43.02% (males 55.48% and females 29.81%).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The top universities in Afghanistan are the American University of Afghanistan (AUAF) followed by Kabul University (KU), both of which are located in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The National Military Academy of Afghanistan, modeled after the United States Military Academy at West Point, was a four-year military development institution dedicated to graduating officers for the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Afghan Defense University was constructed near Qargha in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Major universities outside of Kabul include Kandahar University in the south, Herat University in the northwest, Balkh University and Kunduz University in the north, Nangarhar University and Khost University in the east.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] After the Taliban regained power in 2021, it became unclear to what extent female education would continue in the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In March 2022, after they had been closed for some time, it was announced that secondary education would be reopened shortly.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] However, shortly before reopening, the order was rescinded and schools for older girls remained closed.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Despite the ban, six provinces, Balkh, Kunduz, Jowzjan, Sar-I-Pul, Faryab, and the Day Kundi, still allow girls' schools from grade 6 and up.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In December 2023, investigations were being held by the United Nations on the claim that Afghan girls of all ages were allowed to study at religious schools.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] As of November 2024, some parts of the country allow women to attend religious schools to pursue dentistry, nursing, and other subjects.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] According to the Human Development Index, Afghanistan is the 15th least developed country in the world.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The average life expectancy is estimated to be around 60 years.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country's maternal mortality rate is 396 deaths/100,000 live births and its infant mortality rate is 66 to 112.8 deaths in every 1,000 live births.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The Ministry of Public Health plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 for every 100,000 live births before 2020.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The country has more than 3,000 midwives, with an additional 300 to 400 being trained each year.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] There are over 100 hospitals in Afghanistan, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The French Medical Institute for Children and Indira Gandhi Children's Hospital in Kabul are the leading children's hospitals in the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Some of the other leading hospitals in Kabul include the Jamhuriat Hospital and Jinnah Hospital.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] In spite of all this, many Afghans travel to Pakistan and India for advanced treatment.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It was reported in 2006 that nearly 60% of the Afghan population lives within a two-hour walk of the nearest health facility.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] The disability rate is also high in Afghanistan due to the decades of war.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] It was reported recently that about 80,000 people are missing limbs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p02] Non-governmental charities such as Save the Children and Mahboba's Promise assist orphans in association with governmental structures.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have both common cultural features and those that differ between the regions of Afghanistan, each with distinctive cultures partly as a result of geographic obstacles that divide the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Family is the mainstay of Afghan society and families are often headed by a patriarch.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In the southern and eastern region, the people live according to the Pashtun culture by following Pashtunwali (the Pashtun way).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Key tenets of Pashtunwali include hospitality, the provision of sanctuary to those seeking refuge, and revenge for the shedding of blood.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Pashtuns are largely connected to the culture of Central Asia and the Iranian Plateau.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The remaining Afghans are culturally Persian and Turkic.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Some non-Pashtuns who live in proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali in a process called Pashtunization, while some Pashtuns have been Persianized.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Those who have lived in Pakistan and Iran over the last 30 years have been further influenced by the cultures of those neighboring nations.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan people are known to be strongly religious.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghans, particularly Pashtuns, are noted for their tribal solidarity and high regard for personal honor.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] There are various Afghan tribes, and an estimated 2–3 million nomads.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghan culture is deeply Islamic, but pre-Islamic practices persist.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Child marriage is prevalent; in 2017, Human Rights Watch described the legal age for marriage of girls as being 16, or 15 with the consent of the father or a judge.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The most preferred marriage in Afghan society is to one's parallel cousin, and the groom is often expected to pay a bride price.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In the villages, families typically occupy mudbrick houses, or compounds with mudbrick or stone walled houses.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Villages typically have a headman (*malik*), a master for water distribution (*mirab*) and a religious teacher (*mullah*).
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Men would typically work on the fields, joined by women during harvest.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] About 15% of the population are nomadic, locally called *kochis*.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] When nomads pass villages they often buy supplies such as tea, wheat and kerosene from the villagers; villagers buy wool and milk from the nomads.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghan clothing for both men and women typically consists of various forms of shalwar kameez, especially *perahan tunban* and *khet partug*.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Women would normally wear a *chador* for head covering; some women, typically from highly conservative communities, wear the *burqa*, a full body covering.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] These were worn by some women of the Pashtun community well before Islam came to the region, but the Taliban enforced this dress on women when they were in power.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Another popular dress is the *chapan* which acts as a coat.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The *karakul* is a hat made from the fur of a specific regional breed of sheep.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] It was favored by former kings of Afghanistan and became known to much of the world in the 21st century when it was constantly worn by President Hamid Karzai.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The *pakol* is another traditional hat originating from the far east of the country; it was popularly worn by the guerrilla leader Ahmad Shah Massoud.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The *Mazari hat* originates from northern Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan contains many remnants from all ages, including Greek and Buddhist stupas, monasteries, monuments, temples, and Islamic minarets.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Among the most well known are the Great Mosque of Herat, the Blue Mosque, the Minaret of Jam, the Chil Zena, the Qala-i Bost in Lashkargah, the ancient Greek city of Ai-Khanoum.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in modern times due to the civil wars.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The two famous Buddhas of Bamiyan were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as idolatrous.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] As there was no colonialism in the modern era in Afghanistan, European-style architecture is rare but does exist: the Victory Arch at Paghman and the Darul Aman Palace in Kabul were built in this style in the 1920s.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghan architecture also ranges deep into India such as the city of Agra, and the tomb of Sher Shah Suri, an Afghan Emperor of India.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Carpet weaving is an ancient practice in Afghanistan, and many of these are still handmade by tribal and nomadic people today.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Carpets have been produced in the region for thousands of years and traditionally done by women.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Some crafters express their feelings through the designs of rugs; for example after the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, "war rugs", a variant of Afghan rugs, were created with designs representing pain and misery caused by the conflict.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Every province has its own specific characteristics in making rugs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In some of the Turkic-populated areas in the north-west, bride and wedding ceremony prices are driven by the bride's weaving skills.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Pottery has been crafted in Afghanistan for millennia.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The village of Istalif, north of Kabul, is in particular a major center, known for its unique turquoise and green pottery, and their methods of crafting have remained the same for centuries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Much of *lapis lazuli* stones were earthed in modern-day Afghanistan which were used in Chinese porcelain as cobalt blue, later used in ancient Mesopotamia and Turkey.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The lands of Afghanistan have a long history of art, with the world's earliest known usage of oil painting found in cave murals in the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] A notable art style that developed in Afghanistan and eastern Pakistan is Gandhara Art, produced by a fusion of Greco-Roman art and Buddhist art between the 1st and 7th centuries CE.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Later eras saw increased use of the Persian miniature style, with Kamaleddin Behzad of Herat being one of the most notable miniature artists of the Timurid and early Safavid periods.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Since the 1900s, the nation began to use Western techniques in art.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Abdul Ghafoor Breshna was a prominent Afghan painter and sketch artist from Kabul during the 20th century.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Classic Persian and Pashto poetry are a cherished part of Afghan culture.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Poetry has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] One of the poetic styles is called landay.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] A popular theme in Afghan folklore and mythology are Divs, monstrous creatures.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Thursdays are traditionally "poetry night" in the city of Herat when men, women and children gather and recite both ancient and modern poems.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Pashto literature, although quantitatively remarkable and in great growth in the last century, has always had an essentially local meaning and importance, feeling the influence of both Persian literature and the contiguous literatures of India.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Both main literatures, from the second half of the nineteenth century, have shown themselves to be sensitive to genres, movements and stylistic features imported from Europe.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Khushal Khan Khattak of the 17th century is considered the national poet.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Other notable poets include Rabi'a Balkhi, Jami, Rahman Baba, Khalilullah Khalili, and Parween Pazhwak.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghan classical music has close historical links with Indian classical music and use the same Hindustani terminology and theories like raga.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Genres of this style of music include ghazal (poetic music) and instruments such as the Indian tabla, sitar and harmonium, and local instruments like zerbaghali, as well as dayereh and tanbur which are also known in Central Asia, the Caucasus and the Middle East.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The rubab is the country's national instrument and precurses the Indian sarod instrument.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Some of the famous artists of classical music include Ustad Sarahang and Sarban.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Pop music developed in the 1950s through Radio Kabul and was influential in social change.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] During this time female artists also started appearing, at first Mermon Parwin.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Perhaps the most famous artist of this genre was Ahmad Zahir, who synthesized many genres and continues to be renowned for his voice and rich lyrics long after his death in 1979.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Other notable masters of traditional or popular Afghan music include Nashenas, Ubaidullah Jan, Mahwash, Ahmad Wali, Farhad Darya, and Naghma.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Attan is the national dance of Afghanistan, a group dance popularly performed by Afghans of all backgrounds.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The dance is considered part of Afghan identity.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan has around 350 radio stations and over 200 television stations.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Radio Television Afghanistan, originating from 1925, is the state public broadcaster.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Television programs began airing in the 1970s and today there are many private television channels such as TOLO and Shamshad TV.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The first Afghan newspaper was published in 1873, and there are hundreds of print outlets today.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] By the 1920s, Radio Kabul was broadcasting local radio services.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Voice of America, BBC, and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL) broadcast in both of Afghanistan's official languages on radio.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Press restrictions have been gradually relaxed and private media diversified since 2002, after more than two decades of tight controls.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have long been accustomed to watching Indian Bollywood films and listening to its filmi songs.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] It has been claimed that Afghanistan is among the biggest markets for the Hindi film industry.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The stereotypes of Afghans in India (*Kabuliwala* or *Pathani*) have also been represented in some Bollywood films by actors.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Many Bollywood film stars have roots in Afghanistan, including Salman Khan, Saif Ali Khan, Aamir Khan, Feroz Khan, Kader Khan, Naseeruddin Shah, Zarine Khan, Celina Jaitly, and a number of others.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Several Bollywood films have been shot inside Afghanistan, including *Dharmatma*, *Khuda Gawah*, *Escape from Taliban*, and *Kabul Express*.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghan cuisine is largely based upon the nation's chief crops, such as wheat, maize, barley and rice.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Accompanying these staples are native fruits and vegetables as well as dairy products such as milk, yogurt, and whey.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Kabuli palaw is the national dish of Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The nation's culinary specialties reflect its ethnic and geographic diversity.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan is known for its high-quality pomegranates, grapes, and sweet melons.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] A typical Afghan diet consists of naan, yogurt, rice, and meat.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan's official New Year starts with Nowruz (natively known as "*Nawroz*"), an ancient tradition that started as a Zoroastrian celebration in present-day Iran, and with which it shares the annual celebration along with several other countries.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] It occurs every year at the vernal equinox.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In Afghanistan, Nowruz is typically celebrated with music and dance, as well as holding buzkashi tournaments.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Yaldā, another nationally celebrated ancient tradition, commemorates the ancient goddess Mithra and marks the longest night of the year on the eve of the winter solstice (*Čilli-yi Zimistān*; usually falling on 20 or 21 December), during which families gather together to recite poetry and eat fruit.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] As a predominantly Muslim country, Islamic events and festivals such as Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr and Ashura are widely celebrated annually in Afghanistan.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Sikh festival of Vaisakhi is celebrated by the Sikh community and the Hindu festival Diwali by the Hindu community.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] National Independence Day is celebrated on 19 August to mark the Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919 and the country's full independence.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Several international celebrations are also officially held in Afghanistan, such as International Workers' Day, and International Women's Day.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Some regional festivals include the Red Flower Festival (during Nowruz) in Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Damboora Festival in Bamyan Province.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Sport in Afghanistan is managed by the Afghan Sports Federation.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Cricket and association football are the two most popular sports in the country.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Sports Federation promotes cricket, association football, basketball, volleyball, golf, handball, boxing, taekwondo, weightlifting, bodybuilding, track and field, skating, bowling, snooker, chess, and other sports.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national basketball team won the first team sports title at the 2010 South Asian Games.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In 2012, the country's 3x3 basketball team won the gold medal at the 2012 Asian Beach Games.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] In 2013, Afghanistan's football team followed as it won the SAFF Championship.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan national cricket team, which was formed in 2001, won the 2009–10 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The team played in the 2015, 2019, and 2023 Cricket World Cups.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) is the official governing body of the sport and is based in Kabul.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground serves as the nation's main cricket stadium.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] There are several other stadiums throughout the country, including the Ghazi Amanullah Khan International Cricket Stadium near Jalalabad.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] Domestically, cricket is played between teams from different provinces.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national football team has been competing in international football since 1941.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The national team plays its home games at the Ghazi Stadium in Kabul, while football in Afghanistan is governed by the Afghanistan Football Federation.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The national team has never competed or qualified for the FIFA World Cup but won an international football trophy in 2013.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The country also has a national team in the sport of futsal, a 5-a-side variation of football.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The traditional and the national sport of Afghanistan is buzkashi, particularly popular in the north.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] It is similar to polo, played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass.
[src:afghanistan/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Hound (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan and was used in wolf hunting.
[src:afghanistan/stan] Originally an independent noun, the *stan* morpheme evolved into a suffix because it frequently appeared as the last part in nominal compounds.
[src:afghanistan/stan] It is cognate with the English word *stead*, Polish *stan* (estate, or New World first-level subdivisions), and Sanskrit *sthā́na* (स्थान [stʰaːnɐ]; "the act of standing").
[src:afghanistan/stan] The Sanskrit meaning ultimately derived from Proto-Indo-Iranian **sthāna-*, which was partly loaned into Ancient Greek as Ancient Greek: -στήνη (*-stēnē*).
[src:afghanistan/stan] The suffix *-stan* is analogous to the suffix *-land*, present in many country and location names.
[src:afghanistan/stan] The suffix is also used more generally in Persian and Sanskrit, such as *rēgistān* (ریگستان), "place of sand, desert"; *gulistān* (گلستان), "place of flowers, garden"; *gōristān* (گورستان), "graveyard, cemetery"; and *Hendostân/Hindustan* (هندوستان, हिन्दुस्तान), "Land of the Indus (India)".
[src:afghanistan/stan] In addition, the native names of Armenia and India are respectively *Hayastan*, *Hayk'* being the endonym of Armenians, and *Hindustan*.
[src:afghanistan/stan] The largest *-stan* country by area is Kazakhstan.
[src:afghanistan/stan] The following table lists the subnational entities of different countries that end with *-stan*.
[src:afghanistan/stan] The following list shows some examples of second-level, third-level and fourth-level subdivisions with a *-stan*-like suffix in various countries.
[src:afghanistan/stan] In the Persian language, *Shahrestan* is also a common noun that means "county".
[src:afghanistan/stan] It is in the names of the counties of Iran.
[src:afghanistan/stan] Dehestan is the name of an administrative division in Iran.
